udy of English in Secondary Schools in Early Twentieth-century Japan -- t11 The British Juggernaut: ESP Practice and Purpose in the 1970s -- tV CONTEXT -- t12 Sociocultural, Political, and Educational Aspects of Teaching English in Polish Schools in the Interwar Period (1918–1939) -- t13 English as a Foreign Language in Georgia: From Past to Present -- t14 Language Teacher Education Improvements Would Valorize Practice: A Recent History of Intercultural Language Teaching in Aotearoa/New Zealand -- t15 Social Attitudes toward ‘School English’ in Classroom Practice in South Korea from 1970 to the Present -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn contrast with other works on the history of language learning and teaching, this book is innovative in assigning a much more important role to practice and to the reciprocal relationship of policies and practice (rather than investigating top.down processes from policies to practice). The 14 contributions highlight various contexts of language education in the 20th century, combining inside.out (‘emic’) perspectives, drawing on teachers’/learners’ experience within the classroom, and outside.in (‘etic’) perspectives, looking at external factors such as the curriculum or education policies and considering how teachers and learners respond to these. Each chapter starts from one perspective, yet at the same time takes into account the reciprocal effects between the two directions of movement (inside.out / outside.in). This volume asks, how has the practice of language learning and teaching been influenced by policies and context – and vice versa?  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aLanguage and languagesxStudy and teachingxGovernment policy. 0aLanguage policyxHistoryy20th century. 4aEducational 